Normally, photo-generated electrons and holes gather at the conduction band (E

                        CB
                     ) and the valence band (E

                        VB
                     ) of the semiconductor photocatalyst, respectively (Wei et al., 2021). However, the separation efficiency of the electron-hole pair is relatively low owing to the strong recombination capability (Dalle et al., 2019; Jin et al., 2021). To enhance the separation efficiency of the photo-generated electron-hole pairs and boost PECE, the modification of the photoresponsive material and the optimization of the reactor structure have been recognized as the effective methods (Zhang et al., 2020a).

Ion exchange membrane is widely used to separate inorganic salt from the water, exhibiting a good desalination performance (Ma et al., 2019; Yoon et al., 2019). Herein, to reduce the effect of the inorganic ion on the photoanode performance, an ion exchange membrane optimized PECS was put forward (MPECS). In addition, a TCDW nanocomposite photoanode with good PECE was used as a photoanode. The light harvest efficiency (LHE), photogenerated electron transfer efficiency (ETE), Faraday efficiency (ε

                        F
                     ) in terms of metal ion recovery, and PECE were calculated to evaluate the MPECS performance. The results provide a feasible light-driven method to achieve simultaneous wastewater treatment and metal ion recovery.
